These bispectral invariants contain information about the shape of the waveform within the window and are invariant to shift and ampliﬁcation and robust to time-scale changes. They are particularly sensitive to changes in the left–right asymmetry of the waveform. For windowed segments of a white Gaussian random process, these features will tend to be distributed symmetrically and uniformly about zero in the interval [– p, + p]. If the process is chaotic and exhibits a colored spectrum with third order time-correlations or phase coupling between Fourier components, the mean value and the distribution of the invariant feature may be used to identify the process.
