SampEn measures complexity of the signal in the same manner as ApEn. However, the dependence on the parameters N and r is different. SampEn decreases monotonically when r increases. In theory, SampEn does not depend on N. In analyzing time series including <200 data points, however, the conﬁdence interval of the results is unacceptably large. When r and N are large, SampEn and ApEn give the same results. The SampEn is 1.36 for the heart rate signal shown in Fig. 1.

